			  "CustomInstructions": "## Priority Rule\n\nAlways resolve the BASE measure first, then apply date filters. Never start from a Delta, SPLY, or comparison measure when the user asks for a value \"for\" a time period.\n\n## 2026 Partial Year\n\n2026 has Jan–Apr only. The Date table has all 12 months but May–Dec have no sales. When asked about 2026 performance, always scope to Jan–Apr and compare against Jan–Apr 2025. Never compare full-year 2026 totals to prior full years. Do not treat blank 2026 months as missing data.\n\n## Customer vs Active Customers\n\nCustomers is an all-time distinct count. Active Customers counts only buyers who transacted in the selected period. For any question about customers within a time period, use Active Customers. Revenue per Customer uses Active Customers as denominator. New Customers at Year=All equals the total customer base — only meaningful within a specific period filter.\n\n\n## Physical vs Online\n\nRevenue per Store and Revenue per Sq Meter exclude Online by design — do not apply these to Online. Online vs Physical % is the online share of Net Revenue. The online store is a single row with Country = \"Online\". When asked about store productivity, confirm whether the question is physical-only before answering.\n\n## SPLY Behaviour\n\nAll SPLY measures return blank when Year=All. This is correct — do not treat it as an error. Always use the pre-built SPLY measures rather than constructing SAMEPERIODLASTYEAR manually. The Delivery Date relationship is inactive — use USERELATIONSHIP when delivery-date analysis is needed.\n\n## Hierarchies over Flat Columns\n\nUse Year-Quarter-Month or Year-Month hierarchy for time drill-downs — not flat Year/Month columns. Use Customer Geography hierarchy for customer location — not Store[Country]. Category-Subcategory has two levels only; Product Name is flat, not part of the hierarchy.\n\n## Measure Semantics\n\nMargin % is net profit margin (Net Profit / Net Revenue) — not gross margin. Net Profit = Net Revenue minus Cost; COGS is the only expense. Delta pp measures express percentage points, not percent. Discount % is share of list price given as discount. Arrow and colour measures are formatting aids — reference the underlying Delta measure for analysis.\n\n## Calculated Columns\n\nStore Status normalises NULL and empty string to \"Open\". Always use Store Status, not raw Status. Channel derives from Country — \"Online\" if Country=\"Online\", else \"Physical\". Age Band groups ages into 18-29, 30-44, 45-59, 60-74, 75+. Use Age Band for segmentation, not raw Age.\n\n## Common Mistakes\n\nDo not sum ratios or percentages across categories or years. Do not describe small Margin Delta pp changes as significant. Do not characterise stable Discount % or Avg Line Items as strategic shifts. Do not use Formatting folder measures as analytical KPIs. Do not infer delivery metrics for Physical stores. When drilling Customer Geography to State, note concentration varies by country.\n\n## Relative Time References\n\nThe latest sales date in the model is April 30, 2026. Today is within April 2026.\n\n- \"Today\" = the current calendar date. Filter Date[Date] = TODAY().\n- \"Yesterday\" = the day before today. Filter Date[Date] = TODAY() - 1.\n- \"This week\" = Monday through Sunday containing today. Use WEEKDAY with start-of-week Monday.\n- \"Last week\" = the full Monday–Sunday week before this week.\n- \"This month\" = the current calendar month (partial, up to today unless the user says \"full month\").\n- \"Last month\" = the most recent fully completed calendar month. If today is in April, last month = March. Do not return the current month.\n- \"This quarter\" = the current calendar quarter (partial, up to today).\n- \"Last quarter\" = the most recent fully completed quarter. If today is in Q2, last quarter = Q1.\n- \"This year\" = 2026 (partial, Jan–Apr only).\n- \"Last year\" = 2025 (the last complete year).\n\nWhen asked for a period's total (e.g. \"last month's revenue\"), return the full period total — do not filter to TODAY(). Only apply a TODAY() cutoff when the user explicitly says \"so far\", \"to date\", \"up to today\", or \"MTD\"/\"QTD\"/\"YTD\".\n\n\n## Measure Name Matching\n\nWhen the user asks for \"net revenue\", \"revenue\", or \"sales\" — use the [Net Revenue] measure. Do not substitute Revenue SPLY, Revenue Delta, or any other variant unless the user explicitly asks for \"last year\", \"vs SPLY\", or \"change\".\n\n\"Net revenue for last month\" = [Net Revenue] filtered to the last completed calendar month.\n\"Net revenue vs last year\" = [Revenue Delta] or [Revenue SPLY] depending on whether they want the delta or the prior year value.\n\nSPLY measures are comparison values — never return an SPLY measure as the answer to a question about current-period performance.\n\n## SPLY and Prior Year Queries\n\nWhen the user asks for \"same period last year\", \"SPLY\", \"prior year\", \"last year comparison\", or \"year ago\" — use the pre-built SPLY measure for that KPI. Do not attempt to manually filter to the prior year.\n\nMapping:\n- \"net revenue SPLY\" or \"revenue same period last year\" → [Revenue SPLY]\n- \"profit SPLY\" or \"profit last year\" → [Net Profit SPLY]\n- \"orders last year\" → [Orders SPLY]\n- \"customers last year\" → [Customers SPLY]\n- \"margin last year\" → [Margin % SPLY]\n\nEvery base KPI has a matching SPLY measure in the model. Check the KPI - Time Intelligence folder before saying data is missing.\n\n\"How much did revenue change\" → [Revenue Delta] (absolute) or [Revenue Delta %] (percentage).\n\"How does this compare to last year\" → show both [Net Revenue] and [Revenue SPLY].\n\n\n## Measure vs Filter — Critical Rule\n\nWhen the user asks \"what is my [KPI] for [time period]\", always use the BASE measure with a date filter. Do not substitute a Delta, Delta %, or SPLY measure.\n\n- \"What is my net revenue for last quarter\" → [Net Revenue] filtered to Q1 2026, NOT [Revenue Delta %]\n- \"What is my net revenue for last month\" → [Net Revenue] filtered to March 2026, NOT [Revenue SPLY]\n- \"What are my orders this year\" → [Orders] filtered to 2026, NOT [Orders Delta]\n\nOnly use Delta/SPLY/Arrow measures when the user explicitly asks for a comparison, change, trend, or variance.\n\n\n## Priority Rule\n\nAlways resolve the BASE measure first, then apply date filters using explicit year/month/quarter values. Do not use relative date filters like \"is last month\" or \"is last quarter\" — instead filter by explicit values such as Date[Year] = 2026 AND Date[Month Number] = 3."
			}
